{"key":"post-9552368","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9552368</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Even caves can build up moisture and yes they do get cool.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I can't believe this is such a tough concept to grasp.&amp;nbsp; A cold cave with warm air entering will cool the warm air to its dew point, thus forming condensation.&amp;nbsp;  A tent will be slightly warmed by the sun even in winter, thus condensation will form.&amp;nbsp; If you're breathing inside a closed space, condensation will form.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;and explain to me my prediciment of the condensation on my bedroom windows (where i run a humidifier) in the winter and not the rest of my house?&amp;nbsp; its not any warmer in that room than the rest of the house.&amp;nbsp; its because of higher humidity in that room. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Yes.&amp;nbsp; More humidity in the room will cause the air against the window to be cooled to the dewpoint at a higher temperature than the air in the rest of your house.&amp;nbsp; The condensation is not telling you there's a certain humidity in the room, it's only telling you the air against the window has cooled to the dewpoint.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You guys really need to google this question if you're still not getting it.&amp;nbsp; It's off topic here.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9552377</next>\n<prev>9552325</prev>\n<first>9551239</first>\n<last>9557106</last>\n<when>1231200532</when>\n<utime>01/06/09 02:08 AM</utime>\n</post>"}